  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These obligations typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Understanding the nature of customers' business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n2. Know Your Customer (KYC) Requirements\n- Collecting detailed customer information\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring transactions for suspicious activities\n\n3. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potentially illegal financial activities\n\n4. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Training staff on detection and prevention\n- Maintaining comprehensive recordkeeping\n\n5. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking and analyzing financial transactions\n- Identifying unusual or potentially suspicious patterns\n- Investigating high-risk transactions\n\n6. Risk Assessment\n- Evaluating potential money laundering risks\n- Developing risk-based approaches to monitoring\n- Implementing appropriate prevention strategies\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced through regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar laws in other countries.",
